 and if the agent will record if it’s in the JVM. It seems like our tests in the JVM might not have covered certain aspects because the call sites were active while the test class was executing. It’s possible that the agent can capture some data, but coverage matching might fail due to native issues. This definitely needs further exploration!\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Considering API improvements**\\n\\nI need to mention that active call sites require metadata, but the source has a public API. It sounds like a patch is necessary. Maybe I should remove the helper direct reflection and use a normal JNDI path instead. I’m thinking about adding tests for `getObjectInstance` through `JDBCDataSource.getReference()` and `JDBCPool.getReference`. Perhaps the manual reference isn't seen as a \\\"normal public API.\\\" For `createDataSource`, I might consider using \\\"url\\\" instead of \\\"database\\\" for properties.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Investigating test coverage**\\n\\nI'm questioning whether the `createDataSource` and `newInstance` methods are covered since our test imported `JDBCDataSourceFactory` and called its static methods directly. I think the class should initialize properly, but I wonder if instrumentation is filtering the line and showing \\\"Unknown Source.\\\" I'll need to dig deeper into the build logs and examine the reflection calls for a clearer understanding of the IDs and to check for any specific line info that could help.\"}]}"}, {"type": "toolCall", "id": "call_iCgTupEgqMu42g1bQAjkaDUI|fc_0e0e7679922cc916016a116f1e27fc8196aa0ec02a236432bc", "name": "read", "arguments": {"path": "tests/src/org.hsqldb/hsqldb/2.4.1/build/native/nativeTestCompile/dynamic-access/hsqldb-2.4.1/reflection-calls.json", "limit": 200}}], "api": "openai-responses", "provider": "OCA", "model": "gpt-5.5", "usage": {"input": 735, "output": 3243, "cacheRead": 47616, "cacheWrite": 0, "totalTokens": 51594, "cost": {"input": 0, "output": 0, "cache